She flipped to an empty page and noted the date. Underneath she wrote „11.5.648–13.12.648“.
„Are you stirring up old memories?“ Ivory inquired and looked at the old notebook. Kari nodded. „Do you think they'll let you out for Christmas? There are only a few days left.“
Kari knocked twice on the lantern. „No“, as Ivory had suspected. The Ice King never let Kari out, as he considered her a „blemish“. She was born deaf and was the only daughter in the family, her siblings were all boys.
The same applied to Ivory as well. When Ivory came out as non-binary, it seemed as though the world was changing. As punishment for this nonconformity, Ivory was given tasks where one spent most of the time alone.
Additionally, Ivory was forced to serve the princess. However, it didn't make that much of a difference to Ivory, as Ivory also gained a friend.
“You have a birthday soon, right?” Ivory asked, thinking that the princess would have a birthday in a few days. Kari nodded with a saddened flicker in her light blue eyes.
“Do you want to celebrate your birthday?” Ivory asked and thought about the last time the princess answered this question.
“No,” Kari knocked. Ivory knew that this was a difficult topic for her. Her birthday was the day she was imprisoned in this room and her mother was banished. Ivory was a baby at that time, but she remembered how outraged the servants and the city's residents were. Ivory had heard that Eirwen was a popular queen. And that she strangely also could predict things that actually came true.
“Well, what do you want to do?” Ivory asked. Kari looked excitedly at Ivory. She held a piece of paper in her hand. On it was written:
15 x 15 cm canvas
Weiß, various blue tones
Bristle in six different sizes
Easel
“Are you going to get me these things?” Ivory asked the silent princess, whose braids swung back and forth with her rapid knocking. “Yes?” Ivory giggled softly. The usually closed-off princess showed so much enthusiasm. It was the first time she had asked for something that had nothing to do with books and came from outside her room.
“Okay! See you later?” Ivory asked, stood up and slithered through the chaos of paper and notebooks.
Kari nodded, turned back to her notes, and wrapped herself in her bedspread.
Ivory left the room, relieved that the princess was finally stepping out of her comfort zone and asking for things out of her reach, like watercolors.
Ivory walked down the corridors again, trying to ignore the gossip of the maids.
“I heard she is possessed by Queen Eirwen and that's why she keeps on going back to this room.”
“I heard she eats children in this room.”
"She looks like a man, that's not normal?"
Ivory held her hands over her ears because she couldn't help but hear the gossip and continued on. The royal painter's room was located in the east wing, behind the second door on the left.
Ivory approached the door, which was just as intricately decorated as Karis' door. On it was the White Dragon, one of the six primordial dragons that were supposedly created by Frostfell. For a history-loving painter, the White Dragon on the door made sense.
Ivory opened the door and expected the usual mess. Color splatters everywhere, paintbrushes and paper scattered all over the room, easels covering every inch of the wall. However, an unexpected scene presented itself. The entire room was clean, and in the background of a red velvet backdrop stood a chair. On the chair sat Crown Prince Aquilo, who was being painted.
"Good morning, Ivory! Do you want to watch your future king being painted?" Aquilo asked, winking at Ivory.
"Excuse me, little prince," said Ivory, ignored him mostly and looked for things that the quiet princess wanted. "I'm only here to pick up some things."
"My little girl wants to leave already?", asked Aquilo. "I want you to stay!"
"I don't though." Ivory found the things to pick up on the list and put them into a box. "Besides, I'm not a girl."
However, the prince had a different opinion. "Ah sweetie, that's just a phase! As you grow older, you'll outgrow it!" he said vaguely.
"I have to go," said Ivory and felt uncomfortable with the prince's answer.  In doing so, all the unpleasant remarks that he and others had made about Ivory's gender identity in the past came to mind. I just want to get out of here.
“You're going already?” Suddenly, the prince appeared at the door and ignored the loud protests of the royal painter.
“That's no behavior for a future king!” Ivory said.
“No one will find out. People won't believe you and the painter will keep quiet if his life is worth anything.” He looked at the painter briefly and then leaned in closer to Ivory. “What do you think about a date?” Ivory had been harassed in the past several times, but never by a prince, and certainly not by the crown prince.
“Do you actually know what the word 'No' means?” Ivory spat out and pushed the crown prince away.
“No,” Aquilo replied with a smile. Of course, the crown prince, who could have everything he wants, doesn't know what the word 'No' means.
Ivory rolled her eyes. "Why would you want to go out with someone like me? You must have at least 100 admirers?"
"Actually, it's 50," interrupted Aquilo, still smiling. He tossed his hair back, which swirled around in the cold air.
"Now understand it! Why me precisely? I'm a threat to the palace." Ivory crossed her arms.
"You're the most beautiful girl I've ever seen." Aquilo lifted Ivory's chin with his finger and forced her to look at him.
